metadata.name: De/Frag #328
metadata.description:
De/Frag is an homage to a classic algorithm in early computer art: Flood Fill. As a teenager in the late '80s, and without any literature, I spent weeks implementing a version for my very own drawing program for the Atari XL. It was the first non-trivial (to me) algorithm which made me want to learn more about data structures, the concept of recursion, divide-and-conquer...

Even though Flood Fill was available in most commercial drawing & office apps of the time, I gained a deep appreciation of the algorithm by building it from scratch myself. 30+ years later I know its aesthetic possibilities are still far from exhausted. This is an invitation for re-exploration by others too!

As with many design algorithms, my primary interest isn't even the final result, but observing the inner workings. I massively slowed down and time-sliced the process for this piece. I do recommend giving each of these unique versions some time to allow them to evolve their ever-changing patterns (Note: each piece never loops!).

metadata.name: Love & Wild #100
metadata.description:
We often use flowers to express untold feelings towards our loved ones and most precious people in our life. But love as flowers can go wild & in unpredictable directions.

Love & Wild code come to life few weeks ago when I was alone drinking coffee at local bar, started messing with vertex Quadratic bezier and first petal appeared on screen. After few Loved flowers, the Wild ones start to emerge. Those with sharp spines that are beautiful in it’s own way but can also, like Love, inflict pain. As I was on vacation during finalising this work the colors and flavours of the Mediterranean inspired me.
But except some Wild palettes too.

Thank You

‘s’ for save canvas.
‘2’ for HD png.
‘4’ for 4000x4000px png.
‘8’ for 8000x8000px png.

Created with wild love for p5js and generative art :)
@Qotonana
July, 2022.

metadata.name: Morixels Colab #2 MoriCar #112
metadata.description:
We all dream of having a car or we have

Some of us even talk to our car

And some of us see our car like a cartoon character.

This collection is not only an NFT but also a match
If you win one of the cups, in addition to a Super Rare edition, there are also prizes for the owners in the Primary market, which are as follows:
The lucky winners of the Gold Cup amount to 10 Tezos
The lucky winners of the Silver Cup amount to 5 Tezos
The lucky winners of the Bronze Cup amount to 3 Tezos

The MoriCar is unique random Generated 200 PFP NFTs. The number of Traits in this collection is 7 (78 layers) and it has the ability to make unique 3,492,720 NFTs.

To create balance, these NFTs are randomly minted, and this is a chance for everyone to get a rare version. So due to the low price of these NFTs, if the rare version did not belong to you, it is still possible for you to mint the new NFTs.

Because this is an NFT in PFP format, you can put it on your avatar on Twitter or Instagram.

This project is a collaboration project and it is a Benefit for the owners of the most Morixels to Collaborate with Morixels Designer.

You can read more information on Morixels website 👇

Website: https://morixels.com/

Twitter: @Morixels

by: @morteza_yousefy & @ardavan_
Made in 2022

metadata.name: Pixel Heartbeats (animated) #189
metadata.description:
A uniquely generated animated pixel art piece, reminiscent of a beating heart. Based on a 2013 gif piece of mine, the rigidness of the collection's extra large pixels meet organic generative shapes and natural feeling rhythms, resulting in a mood somewhere between the biological and digital worlds.


Each piece features a unique, sharply rendered generative pixel art with a special heartbeat animation rhythm. The collection also includes exciting color and resolution rarity variations.


--


60% Standard red heart colors
35% Unique rare color variants
5% Special "Shiny" animated color


45% low-fi pixel art animations
45% mid-fi pixel art animations
10% hi-fi pixel art animations


Thanks for stopping by and hope you enjoy!

metadata.name: Millefoglie #221
metadata.description:
"A mille-feuille (French pronunciation: ​[mil fœj], "thousand-sheets"), also known by the names Napoleon, vanilla slice, and custard slice, is a dessert made of puff pastry layered with pastry cream. Its modern form was influenced by improvements made by Marie-Antoine Carême.

Traditionally, a mille-feuille is made up of three layers of puff pastry (pâte feuilletée), alternating with two layers of pastry cream (crème pâtissière). The top pastry layer is finished in various ways: sometimes it is topped with whipped cream, or it may be dusted with icing sugar, cocoa, pastry crumbs, or sliced almonds. It may also be glazed with icing or fondant alone, or in alternating white (icing) and brown (chocolate) or other colored icing stripes, and combed to create a marbled effect." — Wikipedia

Prints available upon request: prints@stefancontiero.com
Best enjoyed on browsers supporting Display-P3 color gamut.

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

@stefan_contiero

metadata.name: Gradient Ascent #92
metadata.description:
Generates a lo-fi sci-fi landscape and applies effects to the result. Most are 2:3 portrait aspect ratio with a smaller chance for landscape or square.

Several cool bonus features are included. Click to draw the image without post processing which can also be downloaded. The unique effect for each iteration can be applied to any image, just drag and drop! There are also URL commands included for advanced users.

Controls

Click = Toggle Processing
Drag & Drop = Process an Image
1 = Toggle processing
2 = Increase resolution
3 = Save as a png

URL Commands

width and height = Change the output size
hd = Set to 1 to show HD by default

Programmed in Vanilla JavaScript by KilledByAPixel
Code and Outputs are Copyright (C) 2022 Frank Force
Artwork is released under CC BY-NC 4.0

metadata.name: Moonlit Sea #108
metadata.description:
A few years ago, my son and I went on a long-term trip to Taitung, Taiwan. One night on the roof of the B&B, we saw the moonlight falling on the pacific ocean. It was very beautiful and peaceful. We will never forget this scene.

Made with memory and p5js.

Variables:
- 24 palettes + random colors
- 5 moon shapes
- 2 island patterns
- 5 wave strength

Control(in live view):
- Press [s] to save a high-res png image
